04933nam a22006495i 9780520926271DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209262717 a10.1525/97805209262712doi  a(DE-B1597)649401  a(OCoLC)1419788932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBM176b.C614 1999eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a296/.09/0142211 aCohen, Shaye J, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeginnings of Jewishness :bBoundaries, Varieties, Uncertainties /cShaye J Cohen; ed. by Shaye J. D. Cohen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (458 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHellenistic Culture and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ON God AND PARENTHESES -- tPROLOGUE: JEWS AND OTHERS -- tPART I: WHO WAS A JEW? -- t1 Was Herod Jewish? -- t2 "Those Who Say They Are Jews and Are Not": How Do You Know a Jew in Antiquity When You See One? -- t3 Ioudaios, Iudaeus, Judaean, Jew -- tPART II: THE BOUNDARY CROSSED: BECOMING A JEW -- t4 From Ethnos to Ethno-religion -- t5 Crossing the Boundary and Becoming a Jew -- t6 Ioudaizein, "to Judaize" -- t7 The Rabbinic Conversion Ceremony -- tPART III: THE BOUNDARY VIOLATED: THE UNION OF DIVERSE KINDS -- t8 The Prohibition of Intermarriage -- t9 The Matrilineal Principle -- t10 Israelite Mothers, Israelite Fathers: Matrilineal Descent and the Inequality of the Convert -- tEPILOGUE: JEWS, JUDAISM, AND JEWISHNESS: US AND THEM -- tAPPENDIX A: WAS MARTIAL'S SLAVE JEWISH? -- tAPPENDIX B: WAS MENOPHILUS JEWISH? -- tAPPENDIX C: WAS TROPHIMUS JEWISH? -- tAPPENDIX D: WAS TIMOTHY JEWISH? -- tGLOSSARY OF SOME HEBREW TERMS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY AND ABBREVIATIONS -- tGENERAL INDEX -- tINDEX OF PREMODERN SOURCES -- tINDEX OF MODERN SCHOLARS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn modern times, various Jewish groups have argued whether Jewishness is a function of ethnicity, of nationality, of religion, or of all three. These fundamental conceptions were already in place in antiquity. The peculiar combination of ethnicity, nationality, and religion that would characterize Jewishness through the centuries first took shape in the second century B.C.E. This brilliantly argued, accessible book unravels one of the most complex issues of late antiquity by showing how these elements were understood and applied in the construction of Jewish identity—by Jews, by gentiles, and by the state.Beginning with the intriguing case of Herod the Great's Jewishness, Cohen moves on to discuss what made or did not make Jewish identity during the period, the question of conversion, the prohibition of intermarriage, matrilineal descent, and the place of the convert in the Jewish and non-Jewish worlds. His superb study is unique in that it draws on a wide range of sources: Jewish literature written in Greek, classical sources, and rabbinic texts, both ancient and medieval. It also features a detailed discussion of many of the central rabbinic texts dealing with conversion to Judaism.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConversionxJudaismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aInterfaith marriagexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIntermarriagexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewish convertsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewsxIdentityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJudaismxHistoryyPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.D. 4aAncient. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Shaye J. D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052022